His Anecdotes, which he dedicates to the Emperor Tiberius (A.D. 14-37), consist of nine bookS, entitled Facta et Dicta Memorabilia, or Memorable Doinqs and Sayinys, and are intended to illustrate certain moral qualities, virtues, vices, merits, and demeritS. They are for the most part short stories from Roman history 3 but the records of other nations have supplied many additional examples. His principal authorities were Cicero, Livy, Sallust, Varro, Asinius Pollio, Herodotus, Alexander Polyhistor, and Xeno- phon Lampsacenus, the author of the Periplus.
